<Base title="Who We Are - BeWildfireAware" active="about"
  description="BeWildfireAware was started in 2024 by a retired wildland firefighter and a technologist to make professional fire danger information accessible to Western Colorado.">
  <main class="content">
    <h1>Who We Are</h1>

    <div class="mission">
      <h2>Our mission</h2>
      <p>
        Wildfire danger shouldn't be hard to find or hard to understand. BeWildfireAware translates the
        National Fire Danger Rating System — the same data federal fire managers use to make daily staffing
        and response decisions — into a clear picture anyone can use: today's danger where you live,
        the conditions driving it, and what the next seven days look like. Built in Western Colorado,
        for Western Colorado, and updated every morning.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="team-grid">
      <div class="team-card">
        <img src="/images/team/jim.webp" alt="Jim Ramirez on the fireline" />
        <div class="team-body">
          <h3>Jim Ramirez</h3>
          <p class="team-role">Co-founder · Fire</p>
          <p>Jim spent over 20 years as a wildland firefighter with the U.S. Forest Service, from 1998 until retiring in 2022 — working engine crews, hand crews, hotshot crews, and heli-rappel crews, then serving as a Fire Module Crew Supervisor and finishing his career as a Zone Battalion Chief.</p>
          <p>One of the most rewarding parts of his career was training new firefighters and helping people understand how wildfire behaves and spreads. In 2024 he started BeWildfireAware to bring fire danger information — long confined to Smokey Bear signs along the road — into an accessible, real-time format.</p>
          <p class="team-caption">Terry Ranch Fire, New Mexico — July 2011</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="team-card">
        <img src="/images/team/paul.webp" alt="Paul Zimmer in Gunnison, Colorado" />
        <div class="team-body">
          <h3>Paul Zimmer</h3>
          <p class="team-role">Co-founder · Technology</p>
          <p>Paul is the other half of the team. He doesn't come from a wildland fire background — his work is in technology and product development, with over 25 years of programming, product management, and entrepreneurial experience. He lives in Gunnison, Colorado, where wildfire isn't an abstract concern; it's part of what it means to live here.</p>
          <p>Jim brings decades of hard-earned experience from the fireline; Paul builds the tools — pulling in real-time data and presenting it in a way that's genuinely useful to neighbors, visitors, and anyone making decisions about their property or their day.</p>
          <p class="team-caption">At home in Gunnison — 2025</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How the site works</h2>
    <p>BeWildfireAware gathers data from Remote Automated Weather Stations (RAWS) across the dispatch areas through FEMS, then applies each area's Fire Danger Operating Plan (FDOP) to calculate the Fire Danger Rating, ERC and BI percentiles, and pocket cards. The Fire Danger Rating Areas come directly from the FDOP. Everything updates automatically each morning.</p>
    <p>We welcome comments and suggestions — BWA is one of many tools available to help share information about wildfire, and we want to keep making it better.</p>
    <p><strong>Contact:</strong> Jim Ramirez, 38 North LLC · gunnisonbc71@gmail.com · 307-690-6619</p>

